# Fix Infinite Loading Screen — Implementation Context

You are fixing a bug in a pure static HTML+JS Three.js ball-rolling game. The game gets stuck on "Teeter Loading..." when initialization fails silently.

## Codebase

Pure static HTML+JS served by nginx. No npm, no build step. Three.js v0.183.2 via CDN importmap.

- `index.html` — Main page with Three.js importmap, overlay UI, and all CSS
- `js/main.js` — Game loop and state management, `init()` function is the entry point
- `js/physics.js` — Ball physics, collision detection
- `js/renderer.js` — Three.js scene, mesh creation, level generation
- `js/tracker.js` — MediaPipe head tilt detection (DO NOT MODIFY this file)
- `Dockerfile` + `nginx.conf` — Docker build serving on port 8080

## What To Change

Only modify `index.html` and `js/main.js`. Do NOT modify `js/tracker.js`, `js/renderer.js`, or `js/physics.js`.

### 1. index.html Changes

**Add a retry button inside the `#overlay` div**, after the `.subtitle` div:
```html
<button id="retry-btn" class="retry-btn">Retry</button>
```

**Add CSS for the retry button** inside the existing `<style>` block:
- `.retry-btn` should be styled: `display: none; margin-top: 16px; padding: 10px 32px; font-size: 1em; font-weight: 600; border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.3); background: rgba(255,255,255,0.1); color: #fff; border-radius: 8px; cursor: pointer; pointer-events: auto; font-family: inherit;`
- `.retry-btn:hover` should have `background: rgba(255,255,255,0.2);`
- `.retry-btn.visible` should set `display: inline-block;`
- Also add `#overlay` a rule: `#overlay.error .retry-btn.visible { display: inline-block; }` (this may already work via cascading)

### 2. js/main.js Changes

**Refactor `init()` function** to add these behaviors:

#### a. WebGL Pre-check
Before calling `initRenderer()`, add:
```js
const testCanvas = document.createElement('canvas');
const gl = testCanvas.getContext('webgl2') || testCanvas.getContext('webgl');
if (!gl) {
  showError('WebGL is not supported by your browser.\nPlease use a modern browser with WebGL enabled.');
  return;
}
```

#### b. Global 15-second timeout
Wrap the initialization logic using `Promise.race` with a timeout:
```js
async function init() {
  const INIT_TIMEOUT = 15000;
  let timeoutId;
  const timeoutPromise = new Promise((_, reject) => {
    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
      reject(new Error('__TIMEOUT__'));
    }, INIT_TIMEOUT);
  });

  try {
    await Promise.race([doInit(), timeoutPromise]);
  } catch (err) {
    if (err.message === '__TIMEOUT__') {
      console.error('Initialization timed out after 15 seconds');
      showError('Loading timed out.\nPlease check your connection and try again.');
    }
    // Other errors are already handled inside doInit()
  } finally {
    clearTimeout(timeoutId);
  }
}
```

Move the current `init()` body into a new `async function doInit()` that contains the actual initialization steps.

#### c. Camera error specificity
Replace the existing camera catch block with more specific error handling:
```js
try {
  stream = await navigator.mediaDevices.getUserMedia({
    video: { facingMode: 'user', width: { ideal: 640 }, height: { ideal: 480 } },
  });
} catch (err) {
  if (err.name === 'NotAllowedError' || err.name === 'PermissionDeniedError') {
    showError('Camera access was denied.\nPlease allow camera access and try again.');
  } else if (err.name === 'NotFoundError' || err.name === 'DevicesNotFoundError') {
    showError('No camera found.\nPlease connect a camera and try again.');
  } else {
    showError('Could not access camera.\n' + (err.message || 'Unknown error'));
  }
  return;
}
```

#### d. MediaPipe tracker error handling
Wrap `initTracker()` in its own try-catch:
```js
subtitle.textContent = 'Loading head tracking model...';
try {
  await initTracker(stream);
} catch (err) {
  console.error('Tracker initialization failed:', err);
  showError('Failed to load head tracking model.\nPlease check your connection and try again.');
  return;
}
```

#### e. Update `showError()` to show retry button
```js
const retryBtn = document.getElementById('retry-btn');

function showError(message) {
  state = 'error';
  overlay.classList.remove('hidden');
  overlay.classList.add('error');
  subtitle.textContent = message;
  overlay.querySelector('.title').textContent = '';
  retryBtn.classList.add('visible');
}
```

#### f. Wire retry button
Add near the other event listeners:
```js
retryBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
  location.reload();
});
```

## Conventions
- 2-space indent throughout all files
- ES module imports/exports
- camelCase for functions/variables, UPPER_SNAKE for constants
- `let` for module-level mutable state, `const` for constants
- Match existing code style exactly — look at surrounding code before writing
- Keep the overlay HTML structure minimal and consistent with existing elements
- The `.subtitle` element uses `white-space: pre-line` so `\n` in text content renders as line breaks

## Testing
- `docker build -t teeter .` must succeed
- When all prerequisites are met (camera allowed, WebGL available, network working), the loading screen should disappear and the game should be playable
- The retry button should NOT be visible during normal successful loading
- Error messages should be specific to the failure type
- The 15-second timeout should trigger if initialization hangs

## Gotchas
- Do NOT modify `js/tracker.js` — wrap its exported function with error handling from main.js
- Do NOT modify `js/renderer.js` or `js/physics.js`
- The `showError` function already exists — enhance it, don't create a duplicate
- `overlay` already has a `.hidden` class when the game starts successfully — make sure `showError` removes `.hidden` if it was added during a partial init
- The overlay has `pointer-events: none` — the retry button needs `pointer-events: auto` to be clickable
- `subtitle.textContent` (not `innerHTML`) is used for error messages — newlines work because of `white-space: pre-line` on `.subtitle`
- The timeout sentinel `__TIMEOUT__` is used to distinguish timeout errors from initialization errors that are already handled with `showError()` + `return` inside `doInit()`. Those early returns resolve the promise normally without error, so only genuinely unhandled exceptions and timeout reach the outer catch.
